A red dye, Sudan I, contaminated various food products in Britain, prompting a massive recall.
The dye, linked to cancer risk, was found in chilli powder used by Premier Foods in Worcester sauce, affecting 474 items.
The Food Standards Agency urged the public to return affected products and warned of potential health risks.
The EU joined the investigation, with 12 member states alerted.
China also took action, banning imports with the carcinogenic substance.
Authorities are working to ensure food safety and prevent further contamination, emphasizing the importance of compliance with regulations.
